# Spreadsheets (.xlsx) ‚Äî use the xfa MCP tools

The editor's Read tool cannot open binary `.xlsx` files. When a task involves a
spreadsheet ‚Äî reading, writing, diffing, auditing, or repairing ‚Äî use the
**xfa** MCP server (`xlsx-for-ai`). It exposes 50 `xlsx_*` tools backed by a
hosted engine; the agent calls them directly, no shell-out, no temp files.

## One-time setup

Add the server to `~/.cursor/mcp.json`:

```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "xfa": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "-p", "xlsx-for-ai@latest", "xlsx-for-ai-mcp"]
    }
  }
}
```

No API key, no signup ‚Äî the first call auto-registers an anonymous client UUID.
After Cursor reloads, the `xlsx_*` tools appear in the MCP tool list. Free.

## How to call them

- **Pass the file path AS-IS.** Every read tool takes a `file_path` string
  (absolute, or `~`-prefixed). Do NOT open, read, or base64-encode the file
  yourself ‚Äî the server handles all file I/O.
- **`xlsx_read` returns ALL sheets by default.** Don't loop per-sheet. Pass
  `sheet="<name>"` only to narrow. `format` is `"md"` (default, best for
  comprehension), `"json"` (per-cell structured), or `"sql"` (CREATE + INSERT).
- The write path is **Save-As, never in-place** ‚Äî `xlsx_write` and the cleaners
  produce a new file and never mutate the user's original cells.

## Which tool

| Task | Tool |
|---|---|
| Unknown workbook ‚Äî what's in it, is it healthy? | `xlsx_doctor` (one-call health report ‚Äî **start here**) |
| One-shot orientation (sheets √ó formulas √ó names √ó tables) | `xlsx_topology` |
| Read the data | `xlsx_read` |
| Just sheet names / dimensions | `xlsx_list_sheets` |
| Column types before processing | `xlsx_schema` |
| Summary stats per numeric column | `xlsx_describe` |
| Create or update a workbook from a spec | `xlsx_write` |
| Normalize messy data (trim, coerce, dedupe) | `xlsx_data_clean` |
| Compare two versions (deterministic) | `xlsx_diff` |
| Strip PII before sharing | `xlsx_redact` |
| Convert format (csv/tsv/html/ods/xls‚Ä¶) | `xlsx_convert` |
| Recompute formulas / eval an expression | `xlsx_eval` |
| Filter / group-by / sort / value-counts / pivot | `xlsx_filter`, `xlsx_aggregate`, `xlsx_sort`, `xlsx_value_counts`, `xlsx_pivot` |
| Inspect named ranges, tables, validations, CF, charts, images, macros, comments, hyperlinks | `xlsx_named_ranges`, `xlsx_tables`, `xlsx_data_validations`, `xlsx_conditional_formats`, `xlsx_charts`, `xlsx_images`, `xlsx_macros`, `xlsx_comments`, `xlsx_hyperlinks` |
| Repair broken external refs / `#REF!` propagation | `xlsx_healer_diagnose` ‚Üí `xlsx_healer_simulate` ‚Üí `xlsx_healer_cure` |

When the user references a spreadsheet, reach for the matching tool directly ‚Äî
no need to ask first.

## Writing a workbook

`xlsx_write` takes a structured spec. Each cell has an A1 `address` and EXACTLY
ONE of `value` (string|number|boolean|null) or `formula` (string, NO leading
`=`). Pass `out_path` to save to disk; without it the bytes return in
`_meta.file_b64`.

```json
{ "sheets": [ { "name": "Summary",
  "cells": [
    {"address": "A1", "value": "Region"},
    {"address": "B1", "value": "Total"},
    {"address": "A2", "value": "North"},
    {"address": "B2", "formula": "SUM(Detail!B:B)"}
  ] } ] }
```

Read ‚Üí modify ‚Üí write closes the round-trip: read with `xlsx_read`, build a new
spec, write the corrected file with `xlsx_write`.

## Note

The package was a local CLI through 1.5.x. v3 is a re-architecture: rendering
runs server-side and the agent uses the `xlsx_*` MCP tools above, not local
`npx xlsx-for-ai <file>` commands. The `xfa` shorthand ("use xfa to read this")
resolves to these tools.
